Why America must not re-elect President Bush
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I was despised by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 with a campaign promising a policy of "modesty" in foreign affairs.
If he is re-elected, this is a vote for the Bush doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq -, and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policies at the polls, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks required a strong response.
They have also led to the suspension of the critical process so essential to democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of pending issues.
Bush silenced the criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress any dissent.
In this way, he led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush played Osama bin Laden directly into his hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
It was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, there were spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America all over the world.
These have given way to widespread bitterness.
Clearly more people than on September 11 are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush often claims that the terrorists hate Americans for who they are - a freedom-loving people - rather than for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
The torture of prisoners at Abu Ghraib was not the work of a few "bad apples."
It was part of a system for dealing with prisoners established by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq pay the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's security is in good hands by addressing the fears caused by the September 11 attacks.
In times of danger, people rally around their flag, and Bush has exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign is based on the assumption that people ultimately do not care about the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something must be wrong with America when we fall for it.
For example, about 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein was involved in September 11, even though the September 11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly concluded that no such connection existed.
One would like to scream: "Wake up, America.
Don't you realize that we are being led by the nose?"
The Iraq War was based from start to finish on false assumptions - if it ever comes to an end.
It was a war of choice, not necessity.
More importantly, America was sent to war under a pretext: weapons of mass destruction could not be found, and the link to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to free Iraq.
But one cannot impose democracy on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad they are rid of him.
But America had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we watched helplessly as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
We would have had to deploy a larger number of soldiers for the occupation if we had really cared about the Iraqi people.
We would have had to protect not only the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they used methods - such as breaking into private homes and mistreating prisoners - that insulted and humiliated the population, and thus caused resentment and anger.
The missteps and failures of the Bush administration are numerous.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to rebuild it.
At first, the USA tried to eliminate the Baathists, then sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be controlled, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protegé with a reputation as a "strong man" - a far from democratic choice.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to spin the situation, the situation in Iraq remains bleak.
A large part of the western region of the country was left to the insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly diminishing.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also caused America immense harm, weakened its military strength, and undermined troop morale.
Before the war, America could project the image of overwhelming strength.
Not anymore today.
Afghanistan is slipping from control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed vigor.
The Bush administration can be criticized on many other political issues, but none is as significant as Iraq.
The cost of the war so far amounts to nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush taunted John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry replied that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But even he will not find this easy, for America is stuck in a swamp.
Leading military experts and diplomats have urgently warned Bush not to invade Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process, arguing that any criticism of the commander-in-chief endangers US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should take a moment to pause and ask themselves: Who do we owe this mess to?
A moment of reflection would likely raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy attitude qualify him to remain America's top commander?
